ARGUMENT.

What use are pedigrees, ancestral blood, statues and images, and noble names, if in the face of our great ancestors we live amiss-—gambling all night and going to bed at dawn, when they were up and marching? What joy has Fabius of the Allobrogcs' victor, of the great altar, of his descent from Hercules, if he be covetous a fool, effeminate, if he bring shame on his rough ancestors, turn poisoner, and disgrace his house? Line your whole house with images, yet still virtue alone is true nobility. Be Paullus, Cossus, Drusus in your morals, and give them place before your images, ay, and your own lictors too. First I claim the goodness of your heart: be holy, just, in word and deed, and then I count you noble. Hail, Gaetulicus, or what- soever stock you come from, your country may be proud of you, and all may cry 33 they do who have found Osiris.
